
 list                                             tuple
Mutable (can be changed)	              Immutable (cannot be changed)
Uses []	                                 Uses ()
Slightly slower	                        Slightly faster
More memory	                            Less memory
allows modification of its elements     elements cannot be changed after creation.

[] → Flexible
() → Fixed
Tuples are also hashable, so they can be used as dictionary keys, whereas lists cannot.
If Python used a list as a dictionary key, the hash could change, which would break the dictionary.

Q.If tuples are immutable, can they contain mutable objects?
t = ([1, 2], [3, 4])
Yes.
t[0].append(5)
works because you're modifying the list inside the tuple, not the tuple itself.
